04805nam a22007095i 9781477311400DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212016txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016018052  a97814773114007 a10.7560/3113872doi  a(DE-B1597)588182  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aRG963.G9bC67 2016 4aRG963.G9C67 2016 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a618.200972812231 aCosminsky, Sheila, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMidwives and Mothers :bThe Medicalization of Childbirth on a Guatemalan Plantation /cSheila Cosminsky. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2016  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter 1 Midwives, Knowledge, and Power at Birth -- tChapter 2 María’s World: The Plantation -- tChapter 3 The Role of the Midwife: María and Siriaca -- tChapter 4 Hands and Intuition: The Midwife’s Prenatal Care -- tChapter 5 Soften the Pain: Management of Labor and Delivery -- tChapter 6 Looking after Mother and Infant: Postpartum Care -- tChapter 7 To Heal and to Hold: Midwife as Healer and Doctor to the Family -- tChapter 8 Career or Calling: National Health Policies and Midwifery Training Programs -- tChapter 9 Medicalization through the Lens of Childbirth -- tAppendix I Medicinal Plants and Remedies Mentioned by Midwives -- tAppendix II Common and Scientific Names of Medicinal Plants -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe World Health Organization is currently promoting a policy of replacing traditional or lay midwives in countries around the world. As part of an effort to record the knowledge of local midwives before it is lost, Midwives and Mothers explores birth, illness, death, and survival on a Guatemalan sugar and coffee plantation, or finca, through the lives of two local midwives, Doña Maria and her daughter Doña Siriaca, and the women they have served over a forty-year period. By comparing the practices and beliefs of the mother and daughter, Sheila Cosminsky shows the dynamics of the medicalization process and the contestation between the midwives and biomedical personnel, as the latter try to impose their system as the authoritative one. She discusses how the midwives syncretize, integrate, or reject elements from Mayan, Spanish, and biomedical systems. The midwives’ story becomes a lens for understanding the impact of medicalization on people’s lives and the ways in which women’s bodies have become contested terrain between traditional and contemporary medical practices. Cosminsky also makes recommendations for how ethno-obstetric and biomedical systems may be accommodated, articulated, or integrated. Finally, she places the changes in the birthing system in the larger context of changes in the plantation system, including the elimination of coffee growing, which has made women, traditionally the primary harvesters of coffee beans, more economically dependent on men.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aChildbirthxSocial aspectszGuatemala. 0aMaternal health servicesxSocial aspectszGuatemala. 0aMidwiveszGuatemalaxSocial conditions. 0aPlantation lifexHealth aspectszGuatemala. 0aRural development - Health aspects - Guatemala. 0aRural developmentxHealth aspectszGuatemala. 0aTraditional medicinezGuatemala. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/31138740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477311400423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477311400/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_